		<div class="article clearfix">
			<h1>NSF grant to support program tackling &#8216;heavy metals&#8217; in Chicago</h1>

			<p class="author-date">
				June 9, 2017			</p>

			<div class="pf-content"><div id="attachment_56611" style="width: 397px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://news.uic.edu/nagy-doyle" rel="attachment wp-att-56611"><img class="size-medium wp-image-56611" src="https://news.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-387x258.jpg" alt="Kathryn Nagy &amp; Danny Morales-Doyle" width="387" height="258" srcset="https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-387x258.jpg 387w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-768x512.jpg 768w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-590x393.jpg 590w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-150x100.jpg 150w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-200x133.jpg 200w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-250x166.jpg 250w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-600x400.jpg 600w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-500x333.jpg 500w, https://today.uic.edu/files/2017/06/nagy-doyle-300x200.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 387px) 100vw, 387px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Kathryn Nagy (left) and Danny Morales-Doyle (right) are heading a project that received a National Science Foundation grant to educate high school students and their teachers about urban pollution.</p></div>
<p>The University of Illinois at Chicago has received a nearly $450,000 National Science Foundation grant that will get high school chemistry students and teachers from seven Chicago public schools to study and address urban heavy metal contamination in their communities.</p>
<p>The project, called &#8220;The Poisoned Onion,&#8221; will support educators to teach chemistry within the context of heavy metal contamination in the soil and water of Chicago neighborhoods.</p>
<p>It is a collaboration between teachers and science educators from Chicago Public Schools, chemists and environmental scientists from UIC, Northwestern University, Loyola University and members of the Chicago Environmental Justice Network.</p>
<p>&#8220;The young people in high school chemistry classes are going to study the problems of toxic metals, including mercury and lead, in soil and water samples taken from communities throughout the city,&#8221; said Danny Morales-Doyle, the project&#8217;s principal investigator and UIC assistant professor of education. &#8220;We are going to come together to figure out how we can actually engage students in these authentic science projects in the community.&#8221;</p>
<p>As part of the project, Morales-Doyle and Alejandra Frausto, a chemistry teacher at Sarah E. Goode STEM Academy in the Ashburn neighborhood, plan to hold summer institutes during the three years of its funding life. The institute will bring together high school teachers, scientists, community organizers and several high school students to plan &#8220;Youth Participatory Science&#8221; projects in high school chemistry classes during the following school year.</p>
<p>The lessons will have students collect soil and water samples and have them analyzed at the partner universities&#8217; labs. The students will then review their data and present findings to the community and their peers at a &#8220;Poisoned Onion&#8221; conference at UIC.  The name refers to the Native American origins of the name Chicago, which pertains to the wild onions that grew in the region.</p>
<p>In addition to Morales-Doyle, who is also coordinator of UIC&#8217;s science teacher education program, and Frausto, the project leaders include co-principal investigator Kathryn Nagy, UIC professor and head of Earth and environmental sciences. Others involved with the project include senior faculty associate Shelby Hatch, director of the general chemistry laboratories at Northwestern University; senior faculty associate Alanah Fitch,  professor of chemistry at Loyola University Chicago; and lead community organizer Kimberly Wasserman, executive director of the Little Village Environmental Justice Organization.</p>
<p>Their goal is to have between 500 and 600 high school students participate during the three years of the program.</p>
<p>&#8220;This project is a great way to introduce environmental earth science to students at the same time that they can become excited about learning chemistry,&#8221; Nagy said. &#8220;It&#8217;s really important for students to see how STEM disciplines relate to their own lives. We hope this project stimulates their interest in pursuing chemistry and/or environmental science in their future careers.&#8221;</p>
<p>Another important component of the program is to raise awareness about the health consequences and other negative implications of heavy metal contamination as an issue of environmental racism. While putting the spotlight on some areas of extensive heavy metal contamination that may require remediation, a key segment will be to educate communities on how they can prevent exposure to heavy metals.</p>
<p>The project will position Chicago teachers and students as &#8220;Change Makers&#8221; who are capable of addressing the crises of inequity in science education and environmental contamination that matter deeply to them, according to the NSF.</p>
<p>Most recently issues of urban contamination have become a concern after the crisis in Flint, Michigan, showed lead contamination in the city&#8217;s water supply.</p>
<p>&#8220;Urban residents often are not aware that their homes are built on or near an industrial site where metals were released to the local environment,&#8221; said Nagy.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
			<p class="author-date">
